ce:section.ce:para:
Fig. 1
(a) shows a comparison of conventional PCM thermal management, dynPCM thermal management on a flat surface, and dynPCM thermal management on a finned surface. In both dynPCM cases the applied pressure maintains a thin melt layer close to the heat source whereas in conventional PCM cooling, the melt front migrates away from the heat source and the liquid PCM volume increases. The melt front migration leads to increased thermal resistance between the heat source and the phase change interface and reduced thermal management ability. The finned surface provides additional surface area for melting to occur compared with the flat surface. Fig. 1(b) shows the transient surface temperature response of a dynPCM cooling system. The dotted lines delineate the melting point of the PCM (Tm
) and the steady state surface temperature (Tss
). The curve was obtained from experiments conducted with applied power of 70 W and added mass of 1500 g on the finned heat sink with 7 mm tall fins. The surface rapidly heats up until reaching Tm
, at which point the heating slows and the surface reaches Tss
, which is maintained until the PCM is depleted. The near-constant steady state temperature is achieved as the applied pressure forces the liquid PCM to flow away from the heat source and maintains a constant melt layer thickness in the range of 10 – 250 µm. The constant, thin melt layer enables quasi-steady conductive heat transfer between the heat source and phase change interface.
